@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "History"
@prev Installation
Apptrashcan can only be used via Workbench, and the CLI commands only via
the CLI, or shell.

   @{b}AppIcon:@{ub}

To trash a file or drawer, just drop it on the AppIcon.

If you double click on the AppIcon the 'About' requester will appear. From
here you can either quit AppTrashcan, or cancel and continue using the
program.

   @{b}Menu Item:@{ub}

To empty all the current trashcans, just select the 'Empty Trash' menu item
from the Tools Menu.

   @{b}AppTrashcan ToolTypes:@{ub}

   @{b}TRASHICON=xxx@{ub}

This option allows you to specify the icon to use for the AppIcon. The
default is the system default for Trashcan, i.e. 'ENV:Sys/Def_Trashcan.info'.

   @{b}TRASHNAME=xxx@{ub}

This option allows you to specify the name of the AppIcon. The default is
'Trashcan'.

   @{b}MENUNAME=xxx@{ub}

This option allows you to specify the name of the 'Empty Trash' menu item.
Defaults to 'Empty Trash'.

   @{b}XPOS=xxx@{ub}
   @{b}YPOS=xxx@{ub}

These options allow you to specify the position for the AppIcon. The
default is to allow Workbench to place the AppIcon in the position it sees
best.

   @{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub}

Add this standard tooltype if running AppTrashcan from WBStartUp.

   @{b}AVOID=xxx@{ub}

With this option you are able to specify any Volumes which must not have
their trashcans emptied. For example,

   AVOID=FTPMount:Silicon:

will stop emptying of trashcans on the FTPMount and Silicon volumes.

NB: volume names must be specified, NOT devices names (such as DF0:).

   @{b}CLI Commands:@{ub}

   @{b}Trash@{ub}

Template: FILES/M,QUIET/S

With this command you can specify multiple files/dirs to be trashed. The
file/dir names can include wildcards. The quiet option will stop any output
from the program. For example,

   Trash dcc:#?.o

will move all the #?.o files to the trashcan on the same disk. Note that
Trash can be made resident.

   @{b}EmptyTrash@{ub}

Template: AVOID/M

This command will empty all the trashcans available. Any volume names
passed to it will mean that the corresponding trashcan will not be emptied.
(See AVOID tooltype above). For example,

   EmptyTrash Work:

will empty all trashcans apart from the one on volume 'Work:'.

@endnode

